    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What wine goes best with traditional Christmas turkey and all the trimmings?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">A medium-bodied red like Pinot Noir or Côtes du Rhône works beautifully with turkey, complementing both the meat and cranberry sauce without overwhelming delicate flavors. For white wine lovers, a rich Chardonnay or Viognier provides enough weight to match the turkey while harmonizing with creamy sides like mashed potatoes and stuffing. The key is choosing wines with moderate tannins and good acidity to cut through the richness of gravy and butter-laden sides.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How many bottles of wine should I buy for Christmas dinner?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Plan for approximately one bottle per two guests for dinner service, plus an additional bottle for every four people if you're serving wine during cocktail hour. For a typical Christmas dinner lasting 3-4 hours, expect wine drinkers to consume 2-3 glasses each. Always have at least one backup bottle of your main pairing, especially if you're serving a large group or multiple courses.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I serve different wines with each Christmas dinner course?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">While impressive, multiple wine pairings aren't necessary for most Christmas dinners since courses are often served family-style rather than sequentially. Choose one versatile red and one white wine that complement your main dishes and sides—this approach is more practical and cost-effective. If you do want multiple wines, focus on a lighter wine for appetizers and a fuller-bodied option for the main course and dessert.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when choosing Christmas dinner wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common error is selecting wines that are too heavy or tannic, which clash with the sweet and savory elements typical in Christmas dishes like glazed ham, sweet potato casserole, and cranberry sauce. Avoid bold Cabernet Sauvignon or heavily oaked wines that will overpower delicate flavors. Instead, focus on food-friendly wines with balanced acidity that enhance rather than compete with your carefully prepared meal.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Are there good non-alcoholic wine alternatives for Christmas dinner?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Premium non-alcoholic wines like Fre, Ariel, or Töst offer sophisticated flavors that pair well with Christmas dinner without the alcohol content. Sparkling grape juices from quality producers like Martinelli's or Welch's Premium provide festive bubbles for toasts. For a more complex option, consider alcohol-removed wines that maintain varietal character, or craft mocktails using pomegranate juice, cranberry, and herbs that complement traditional holiday flavors.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">When should I open and serve Christmas dinner wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Open red wines 30-60 minutes before serving to allow proper aeration, especially for medium to full-bodied selections like Merlot or Rhône blends. White wines should be chilled for 2-3 hours in the refrigerator before opening, or 20-30 minutes in an ice bucket. For sparkling wines, chill thoroughly and open just before serving to preserve carbonation and prevent cork accidents during the busy dinner preparation.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's a good budget-friendly wine strategy for Christmas dinner?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Focus on value-driven regions like Portugal's Douro, Southern France, or Washington State, where you can find excellent wines under $20 that pair beautifully with Christmas fare. Buy wines in advance during fall sales, and consider magnums (1.5L bottles) which offer better value per ounce while creating an impressive presentation. Spanish Tempranillo, Portuguese blends, or French Côtes du Rhône deliver complexity and food-friendliness without premium pricing.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can I pair wine with Christmas ham instead of turkey?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Ham's sweetness and saltiness create excellent pairing opportunities with wines that have good acidity and fruit-forward characteristics. Riesling, Gewürztraminer, or Beaujolais work magnificently with glazed ham, as their natural acidity cuts through the richness while their fruitiness complements sweet glazes. For red wine lovers, light to medium-bodied options like Pinot Noir or Sangiovese provide enough structure without overwhelming the delicate pork flavors.</p>
  </div>
